class="comment-bg"><div
class="comment-body"><h3><a
href='http://personalchallenge.wordpress.com' rel='external nofollow' class='url'>Rick L</a> says on <a
href="#comment-183983" title="">July 30th, 2007 at 11:50 am</a></h3><p><p>I once believed that design was about making things pretty. So, my utilitarian sensibilities rejected it as being frivolous.</p><p>Then I read about C.R.A.P. from a well-written little book called The Non-Designer&#8217;s Design Book, which I spent a few minutes browsing through in a local bookstore about ten years ago. Those few minutes have greatly improved every resume, business card, web page, and document that I have created since.</p><p>What I have realized since then is this: Design is not about making something pretty. It is about making something easier to use. This is exactly what the four CRAP principles do for you: They make information in a document easier for a person&#8217;s brain to process. If done properly, the presentation usually becomes pretty as a natural side effect.</p></p></div></div><div
class="comment-bottom"></div></div></li><li><div
